From dtenenba at fredhutch.org  Thu Jun 23 03:35:07 2016
From: dtenenba at fredhutch.org (Dan Tenenbaum)
Date: Wed, 22 Jun 2016 18:35:07 -0700 (PDT)
Subject: [Bioc-devel] git svn dcommit
In-Reply-To: <31290_1466644337_576B3771_31290_18424_1_CAC2h7uvgnoMtmn10FEzHn6e-67i76G6m+WSkL6LDkLiHJoG4pg@mail.gmail.com>
References: <31290_1466644337_576B3771_31290_18424_1_CAC2h7uvgnoMtmn10FEzHn6e-67i76G6m+WSkL6LDkLiHJoG4pg@mail.gmail.com>
Message-ID: <2017898626.169190.1466645707156.JavaMail.zimbra@fredhutch.org>

My understanding is that this happens if you ever had non-linear commit history in your github repository (i.e. more than one branch changed and then were merged together), or if you used the old git/svn bridge. As far as I understand it, the only solution (in the near term) is to cherry pick the commits you want, a la

https://bioconductor.org/developers/how-to/git-mirrors/#dealing-with-prior-history--merge-conflicts

And this has to be done every time you want to sync git to svn.

Dan


